{{nihongo|'''Hiragana'''|[[wikt:Âπ≥‰ªÆÂêç|Âπ≥‰ªÆÂêç]], „Å≤„Çâ„Åå„Å™ or „Éí„É©„Ç¨„Éä|}} is a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[syllabary]], one basic component of the [[Japanese writing system]], along with [[katakana]], [[kanji]], and in some cases the [[Latin-script alphabet]] (referred to in Japanese as [[r≈çmaji]]).

Hiragana and katakana are both [[kana]] systems; they have corresponding character sets in which each ''kana'', or character, represents one [[mora (linguistics)|mora]] (one sound in the Japanese language). Each ''kana'' is either a vowel such as ''"a"'' (hiragana [[wikt:„ÅÇ|„ÅÇ]]); a consonant followed by a vowel such as ''"ka"'' (hiragana [[wikt:„Åã|„Åã]]); or ''"n"'' (hiragana [[wikt:„Çì|„Çì]]), a [[nasal stop|nasal]] [[sonorant]] which, depending on the context, sounds either like English ''m'', ''n'', or ''ng'' ({{IPAblink|≈ã}}), or like the [[nasal vowel]]s of [[French language|French]]. Because the characters of the kana do not represent single consonants (except in the case of „Çì "n"), the kana are referred to as syllabaries and not alphabets.<ref>{{cite book|title=An Introduction to Modern Japanese: Book 1|year=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=United Kingdom|isbn=978-0521548878|author=Richard Bowring|coauthors=Haruko Uryu Laurie|page=9}}</ref>

Hiragana is used to write native words for which there are no [[kanji]], including grammatical [[Japanese particles|particles]] such as {{nowrap|„Åã„Çâ}} ''kara'' "from", and suffixes such as {{nowrap|„Åï„Çì}} ''~san'' "Mr., Mrs., Miss, Ms." Likewise, hiragana is used to write words whose kanji form is obscure, not known to the writer or readers, or too formal for the writing purpose. There is also some flexibility for words that have common kanji renditions to be optionally written instead in hiragana, according to an individual author's preference. [[Okurigana|Verb and adjective inflections]], as, for example, ''be-ma-shi-ta'' {{nowrap|(„Åπ„Åæ„Åó„Åü)}} in {{nihongo|''tabemashita''|È£ü„Åπ„Åæ„Åó„Åü||"ate"}}, are written in hiragana, often following a verb or adjective root (here, "È£ü") that is written in kanji. When Hiragana is used to show the [[pronunciation]] of kanji characters as reading aid, it is referred to as ''[[furigana]]''. The article [[Japanese writing system]] discusses in detail how the various systems of writing are used.

There are two main systems of [[Kana#Collation|ordering hiragana]], the old-fashioned [[iroha]] ordering, and the more prevalent [[goj≈´on]] ordering.

