In the middle of words, the ''g'' sound (normally {{IPA|[…°]}}) often turns into a [[velar nasal]] {{IPA|[≈ã]}} and less often (although increasing recently) into the [[voiced velar fricative]] {{IPA|[…£]}}. An exception to this is numerals; 15 ''juugo'' is considered to be one word, but is pronounced as if it was ''j≈´'' and ''go'' stacked end to end: {{IPA|[dÕ° ëuÕçÀê…°o]}}.

Additionally, the ''j'' sound (normally {{IPA|[dÕ° ë]}}) can be pronounced {{IPA|[ ë]}} in the middle of words. For example {{nowrap|„Åô„ÅÜ„Åò}} ''s≈´ji'' {{IPA|[suÕçÀê ëi]}} 'number'.

In archaic forms of Japanese, there existed the ''kwa'' ({{lang|ja|„Åè„Çé}} {{IPA-ja|k ∑a|}}) and ''gwa'' ({{lang|ja|„Åê„Çé}} {{IPA-ja|…° ∑a|}}) digraphs. In modern Japanese, these phonemes have been phased out of usage and only exist in the extended [[katakana]] digraphs for approximating foreign language words.

The singular ''n'' is pronounced {{IPA|[n]}} before ''t'', ''ch'', ''ts'', ''n'', ''r'', ''z'', ''j'' and ''d'', {{IPA|[m]}} before ''m'', ''b'' and ''p'', {{IPA|[≈ã]}} before ''k'' and ''g'', {{IPA|[…¥]}} at the end of utterances, {{IPA|[≈©Õç]}} before vowels, palatal approximants (''y''), consonants ''s'', ''sh'', ''h'', ''f'' and ''w'', and finally {{IPA|[ƒ©]}} after the vowel ''i'' if another vowel, palatal approximant or consonant ''s'', ''sh'', ''h'', ''f'' or ''w'' follows.<!-- ≈© before ''z'' is possible too.. -->

In kanji readings, the diphthongs ''ou'' and ''ei'' are today usually pronounced {{IPA|[oÀê]}} (long o) and {{IPA|[eÀê]}} (long e) respectively. For example {{nowrap|„Å®„ÅÜ„Åç„Çá„ÅÜ}} (lit. ''toukyou'') is pronounced {{IPA|[toÀêk ≤oÀê]}} 'Tokyo', and {{nowrap|„Åõ„Çì„Åõ„ÅÑ}} ''sensei'' is {{IPA|[se≈©ÕçseÀê]}} 'teacher'. However, {{nowrap|„Å®„ÅÜ}} ''tou'' is pronounced {{IPA|[touÕç]}} 'to inquire', because the ''o'' and ''u'' are considered distinct, ''u'' being the infinitive verb ending. Similarly, {{nowrap|„Åó„Å¶„ÅÑ„Çã}} ''shite iru'' is pronounced {{IPA|[…ïitei…æuÕç]}} 'is doing'.

For a more thorough discussion on the sounds of Japanese, please refer to [[Japanese phonology]].

==Spelling rules==

With a few exceptions for sentence particles „ÅØ, „Çí, and „Å∏ (pronounced as ''wa'', ''o'', and ''e''), and a few other arbitrary rules, Japanese, when written in kana, is [[Phonemic principle|phonemically orthographic]], i.e. there is a one-to-one correspondence between kana characters and sounds, leaving only words' [[Japanese pitch accent|pitch accent]] unrepresented. This has not always been the case: a previous system of spelling, now referred to as [[historical kana usage]], differed substantially from pronunciation; the three above-mentioned exceptions in modern usage are the legacy of that system. The old spelling is referred to as {{nihongo|''[[kanazukai]]''|‰ªÆÂêçÈÅ£„ÅÑ|}}.

There are two hiragana pronounced ''ji'' („Åò and „Å¢) and two hiragana pronounced ''zu'' („Åö and „Å•), but to distinguish them, sometimes ''„Å¢'' is written as ''di'' and ''„Å•'' is written as dzu. These pairs are not interchangeable. Usually, ''ji'' is written as „Åò and ''zu'' is written as „Åö. There are some exceptions. If the first two syllables of a word consist of one syllable without a ''[[dakuten]]'' and the same syllable with a ''dakuten'', the same hiragana is used to write the sounds.  For example ''chijimeru'' ('to boil down' or 'to shrink') is spelled „Å°„Å¢„ÇÅ„Çã and ''tsudzuku'' ('to continue') is {{nowrap|„Å§„Å•„Åè}}. For compound words where the dakuten reflects ''[[rendaku]]'' voicing, the original hiragana is used. For example, ''chi'' ({{lang|ja|Ë°Ä}} 'blood') is spelled „Å° in plain hiragana. When {{lang|ja|Èºª}} ''hana'' ('nose') and {{lang|ja|Ë°Ä}} ''chi'' ('blood') combine to make ''hanaji'' {{lang|ja|ÈºªË°Ä}} 'nose bleed'), the sound of Ë°Ä changes from ''chi'' to ''dji''.  So ''hanadji'' is spelled {{nowrap|„ÅØ„Å™„Å¢}} according to „Å°: the basic hiragana used to transcribe {{lang|ja|Ë°Ä}}. Similarly, ''tsukau'' ({{lang|ja|‰Ωø„ÅÜ/ÈÅ£„ÅÜ}}; 'to use') is spelled {{nowrap|„Å§„Åã„ÅÜ}} in hiragana, so ''kanazukai'' ({{lang|ja|‰ªÆÂêçÈÅ£„ÅÑ}}; 'kana use', or 'kana orthography') is spelled {{nowrap|„Åã„Å™„Å•„Åã„ÅÑ}} in hiragana.

However, this does not apply when kanji are used phonetically to write words which do not relate directly to the meaning of the kanji (see also [[ateji]]).  The Japanese word for 'lightning', for example, is ''inazuma'' ({{lang|ja|Á®≤Â¶ª}}).  The {{lang|ja|Á®≤}} component means 'rice plant', is written {{nowrap|„ÅÑ„Å™}} in hiragana and is pronounced: ''ina''.  The {{lang|ja|Â¶ª}} component means 'wife' and is pronounced ''tsuma'' („Å§„Åæ) when written in isolation‚Äîor frequently as ''zuma'' {{nowrap|(„Åö„Åæ)}} when it features after another syllable. Neither of these components have anything to do with 'lightning', but together they do when they compose the word for 'lightning'. In this case, the default spelling in hiragana {{nowrap|„ÅÑ„Å™„Åö„Åæ}} rather than {{nowrap|„ÅÑ„Å™„Å•„Åæ}} is used.

Officially, „Å¢ and „Å• do not occur word-initially pursuant to modern spelling rules. There were words such as {{nowrap|„Å¢„Å∞„Çì}} ''jiban'' 'ground' in the [[historical kana usage]], but they were unified under „Åò in the [[modern kana usage]] in 1946, so today it is spelled exclusively {{nowrap|„Åò„Å∞„Çì}}. However, {{nowrap|„Å•„Çâ}} ''zura'' 'wig' (from {{nowrap|„Åã„Å§„Çâ}} ''katsura'') and {{nowrap|„Å•„Åë}} ''zuke'' (a sushi term for lean tuna soaked in soy sauce) are examples of word-initial „Å• today. Some people write the word for hemorrhoids as „Å¢ (normally „Åò) for emphasis.

No standard Japanese words begin with the kana „Çì (''n''). This is the basis of the word game [[shiritori]]. „Çì ''n'' is normally treated as its own syllable and is separate from the other ''n''-based kana (''na'', ''ni'' etc.). A notable exception to this{{Clarify|reason = unclear how this is an "exception" to anything that has been said|date=May 2010}} is the colloquial negative verb conjugation; for example {{nowrap|„Çè„Åã„Çâ„Å™„ÅÑ}} ''wakaranai'' meaning "[I] don't understand" is rendered as {{nowrap|„Çè„Åã„Çâ„Çì}} ''wakaran''. It is however not a contraction of the former, but instead comes from the classic negative verb conjugation „Å¨ ''nu'' ({{nowrap|„Çè„Åã„Çâ„Å¨}} ''wakaranu'').

„Çì is sometimes directly followed by a vowel (''a'', ''i'', ''u'', ''e'' or ''o'') or a palatal approximant (''ya'', ''yu'' or ''yo''). These are clearly distinct from the ''na'', ''ni'' etc. syllables, and there are [[minimal pair]]s such as {{nowrap|„Åç„Çì„Åà„Çì}} ''kin'en'' 'smoking forbidden', {{nowrap|„Åç„Å≠„Çì}} ''kinen'' 'commemoration', {{nowrap|„Åç„Çì„Å≠„Çì}} ''kinnen'' 'recent years'. In Hepburn romanization, they are distinguished with an apostrophe, but not all romanization methods make the distinction. For example past prime minister [[Junichiro Koizumi]]'s first name is actually {{nowrap|„Åò„ÇÖ„Çì„ÅÑ„Å°„Çç„ÅÜ}} ''Jun'ichir≈ç'' pronounced {{IPA|[dÕ° ëuÕç≈©ÕçitÕ°…ïi…æoÀê]}}

There are a few hiragana which are rarely used. „Çê ''wi'' and „Çë ''we'' are obsolete outside of Okinawan dialects. „Çî ''vu''  is a modern addition used to represent the /v/ sound in foreign languages such as English, but since Japanese from a phonological standpoint does not have a /v/ sound, it is pronounced as /b/ and mostly serves as a more accurate indicator of a word's pronunciation in its original language. However, it is rarely seen because [[loanword]]s and [[Transliteration|transliterated]] words are usually written in [[katakana]], where the corresponding character would be written as „É¥. {{nowrap|„Å¢„ÇÉ}}, {{nowrap|„Å¢„ÇÖ}}, {{nowrap|„Å¢„Çá}} for ''ja''/''ju''/''jo'' are theoretically possible in [[rendaku]], but are practically never used. For example {{nowrap|Êó•Êú¨‰∏≠}} 'throughout Japan' could be written {{nowrap|„Å´„Åª„Çì„Å¢„ÇÖ„ÅÜ}}, but is practically always {{nowrap|„Å´„Åª„Çì„Åò„ÇÖ„ÅÜ.}}

The {{nowrap|„Åø„ÇÖ}} ''myu'' kana is extremely rare in originally Japanese words; linguist [[Haruhiko Kindaichi]] raises the example of the Japanese family name Omamy≈´da {{nowrap|(Â∞èË±ÜÁîüÁî∞)}} and claims it is the only occurrence amongst pure Japanese words. Its [[katakana]] counterpart is used in many loanwords, however.

==History==
[[File:Treatise On Calligraphy.jpg|thumb|left|Hiragana characters' shapes were derived from the Chinese [[Cursive script (East Asia)|cursive script]] (''s≈çsho''). Shown here is a sample of the cursive script by Chinese [[Tang Dynasty]] calligrapher [[Sun Guoting]], from the late 7th century.]]
Hiragana developed from ''[[man'y≈çgana]]'', [[Chinese language|Chinese]] characters used for their pronunciations, a practice which started in the 5th century.<ref>''Yookoso! An Invitation to Contemporary Japanese'' 1st edition McGraw-Hill, page 13 "Linguistic Note: The Origins of Hiragana and Katakana"</ref> The oldest example of Man'y≈çgana is [[Inariyama Sword]] which is an iron sword excavated at the Inariyama Kofun in 1968. This sword is thought to be made in year of {{nowrap|Ëæõ‰∫•Âπ¥}} (which is A.D. 471 in commonly accepted theory).<ref>Seeley (2000:19-23)</ref>
The forms of the hiragana originate from the [[cursive script (East Asia)|cursive script]] style of [[Chinese calligraphy]]. The figure below shows the derivation of hiragana from many≈çgana via cursive script. The upper part shows the character in the [[regular script]] form, the center character in red shows the cursive script form of the character, and the bottom shows the equivalent hiragana. Note also that the cursive script forms are not strictly confined to those in the illustration.

[[File:Hiragana origin.svg|320px|right]] When they were first developed, hiragana were not accepted by everyone. The educated or elites preferred to use only the kanji system. Historically, in Japan, the regular script (''kaisho'') form of the characters was used by men and called {{nihongo|''otokode''|[[wikt:Áî∑Êâã|Áî∑Êâã]]|}}, "men's writing", while the cursive script (''s≈çsho'') form of the kanji was used by women. Hence hiragana first gained popularity among women, who were generally not allowed access to the same levels of education as men. And thus hiragana was first widely used among court women in the writing of personal communications and literature.<ref>{{cite book|title=An Introduction to Modern Japanese: Book 1|year=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=United Kingdom|isbn=978-0521548878|author=Richard Bowring|coauthors=Haruko Uryu Laurie|page=8}}</ref>  From this comes the alternative name of {{nihongo|''onnade''|[[wikt:Â•≥Êâã|Â•≥Êâã]]|}} "women's writing".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hatasa|first=Yukiko Abe|title=Nakama 1: Introductory Japanese: Communication, Culture, Context 2nd ed.|year=2010|publisher=Heinle|isbn=0495798185|page=2|coauthors=Kazumi Hatasa, Seiichi Makino}}</ref>  For example, ''[[The Tale of Genji]]'' and other early novels by female authors used hiragana extensively or exclusively.

Male authors came to write literature using hiragana. Hiragana was used for unofficial writing such as personal letters, while katakana and Chinese were used for official documents. In modern times, the usage of hiragana has become mixed with [[katakana]] writing. Katakana is now relegated to special uses such as recently borrowed words (i.e., since the 19th century), names in [[transliteration]], the names of animals, in telegrams, and for emphasis.

Originally, for all syllables there was more than one possible hiragana. In 1900, the system was simplified so each syllable had only one hiragana. The deprecated hiragana are now known as {{nihongo|[[hentaigana]]|Â§â‰Ωì‰ªÆÂêç|}}.

The [[pangram]] poem ''[[Iroha]]-uta'' ("ABC song/poem"), which dates to the 10th century, uses every hiragana once (except ''n'' „Çì, which was just a variant of „ÇÄ before [[Muromachi era]]).

